The '''Meiningen Ensemble''', also known as the [[Meiningen]] Company, was the [[Noble court|court]] theatre of the [[Germany|German]] [[Ernestine duchies|state]] of [[Saxe-Meiningen]], led by [[Georg II, Duke of Saxe-Meiningen]]. Its principal director was [[Ludwig Chronegk]]. The Ensemble was a great influence on [[Henrik Ibsen|Ibsen]], [[André Antoine (actor)|Antoine]], and [[Constantin Stanislavski|Stanislavski]].<ref name=Innes10/>

The Duke admired [[Charles Kean]]'s attempts to stage [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]]'s plays in a manner that was historically accurate for the place and period in which each drama was set. The Ensemble that he created, which toured Germany and Europe in 1874–1890, became famous across Europe for its detailed, archeologically authentic reproductions of locations and its realistic, fully individuated crowd scenes.<ref name=Innes10/> Its productions offered a model of an [[Gesamtkunstwerk|integrated, unified]] theatrical [[aesthetic]] and a demonstration of the potential of a tightly controlled, [[Theatre director|director]]-focused mode of theatre-making.

