{{BLP sources|date=January 2016}} {{ infobox person | name = Dr. Steven Fine | image = StevenFineforWikipedia.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = Courtesy of [[Yeshiva University]] | birth_name = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | body_discovered = | death_cause = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LONG|display=inline,title}} --> | residence = | nationality = | ethnicity = | citizenship = | other_names = | known_for = | education = | alma_mater = | employer = [[Yeshiva University]] | occupation = | years_active = | home_town = | salary = | networth = | height = | weight = | title = Dr. Pinkhos Churgin Professor of Jewish History, Director of the Yeshiva University Center for Israel Studies and the Arch of Titus Digital Restoration Project | term = | predecessor = | successor = | party = | opponents = | boards = | religion = | spouse = | partner = | children = | parents = | relations = | callsign = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = www.https://yeshiva.academia.edu/StevenFine/ | footnotes = | box_width = }}
'''Steven Fine''' is a historian of Judaism in the [[Greco-Roman world|Greco-Roman World]] and a professor at [[Yeshiva University]].
==Education== Fine received a BA in Religious Studies from [[University of California, Santa Barbara]] in 1979, an MA in Art History and Museum Studies from the [[University of Southern California]] in 1984, and a PhD in Jewish History from [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]] in 1993.
==Career== Fine worked as an intern in the Departments of Jewish Art and Jewish Folklore at the [[Israel Museum]] (1977-8, 1980–81), in the Department of Indian Art of the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] (1982-3, under the tutelage of Pratapaditya Pal), and then as curator of the USC Archaeological Research Collection (1983-87 under the tutelage of Bruce Zuckerman).{{Citation needed|date = January 2016}}
After completing his doctorate in Jerusalem, Fine served as assistant and associate professor at Baltimore Hebrew College (1994-2000), and then as Jewish Foundation Professor of Judaic Studies at the [[University of Cincinnati]] from 2000 to 2005.{{Citation needed|date = January 2016}}
Steven Fine joined the faculty of Yeshiva University in 2005 as Professor of Jewish History, and served as chair of the Department of Jewish History at Yeshiva College. In 2015 he was awarded the Dean Pinkhos Churgin Chair in Jewish History at Yeshiva University. He is the Founding Director of the Yeshiva University Center for Israel Studies and the Arch of Titus Project.<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|title = Menorah on Arch of Titus in Roman Forum Was Rich Yellow|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/25/arts/design/menorah-on-arch-of-titus-in-roman-forum-was-rich-yellow.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2012-06-24|access-date = 2016-01-15|issn = 0362-4331|first = Elisabetta|last = Povoledo}}</ref>
=== Arch of Titus === Fine is the head of the [[Arch of Titus]] Digital Restoration Project.<ref name=":0" /> The team discovered original [[Ochre|yellow ochre]] paint that was originally on the [[Menorah (Temple)|menorah]] at the arch.<ref name=":0" />
Some of his work, including his class on the Arch of Titus, has been dedicated to debunking the myth that the ancient menorah from the [[Temple in Jerusalem]] is in the [[Vatican City|Vatican.]]<ref>{{Cite news|title = Yeshiva Students Challenge Myths of the Menorah|url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/yeshiva-students-challenge-myths-of-the-menorah-1408069132|newspaper = Wall Street Journal|access-date = 2016-01-15|issn = 0099-9660|first = Sophia|last = Hollander}}</ref>
