The '''Warwickshire Company of Comedians''', also known as '''Mr Ward's Company of Comedians''' and after 1767 as '''Mr Kemble's Company of Comedians''', was a [[theatre company]] established by [[John Ward (actor)|John Ward]] in [[Birmingham]], [[England]] in the 1740s, touring throughout the [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]] region and surrounding counties over subsequent decades.<ref name="Money">{{Citation|last=Money|first=John|year=1977|title=Experience and identity: Birmingham and the West Midlands, 1760-1800|publication-place=Manchester|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=0-7190-0672-4|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T_7oAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA87|page=87|accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref> Unusual in the 18th century as a provincial company producing performances to [[London]] tastes and standards, it is particularly notable as the origin of the [[Kemble family]] theatrical dynasty, which was to dominate the English stage in the late-18th and early 19th centuries.<ref>{{Citation|title=19th Century Theatre|series=Theatre and Performance|publication-place=London|publisher=Victoria and Albert Museum|url=http://www.vam.ac.uk/collections/theatre_performance/features/history_drama/19thC_theatre/early_victorian_drama/index.html|accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref> [[Sarah Siddons]] and [[John Philip Kemble]] in particular, who were Ward's grandchildren and whose careers began in the company, were the leading actress and actor of their time, and are still considered among the greatest performers in English theatrical history.<ref>{{Citation|last=Shaughnessy|first=Robert|year=2008|contribution=Siddons (née Kemble), Sarah (1755–1831), actress|contribution-url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/25516|title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography|edition=Online|publisher=Oxford University Press|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com|accessdate=2011-05-23}}; {{Harvnb|Price|1948|p=44}}</ref>

==History==
===Foundation===
[[File:John Ward by Thomas Beech.jpg|thumb|right|upright|[[John Ward (actor)|John Ward]]]]The Warwickshire Company of Comedians was founded by [[John Ward (actor)|John Ward]] at Birmingham's [[Moor Street Theatre]], which opened in 1740 and which Ward is recorded as managing in the early 1740s.<ref>{{Citation|last=Pendleton|first=Muriel|year=2010|title=From bullbaiting to theater and oratorio attending: The cultural development of Birmingham during the eighteenth century|publication-place=Long Beach, CA|publisher=California State University|pp=38–39|url=http://gradworks.umi.com/14/86/1486356.html|accessdate=2011-05-23}} ; {{Harvnb|Thompson|1999|p=142}}</ref> Although the precise date of its foundation is unknown, the company was definitely in existence by 1744, when they are recorded as visiting [[Stratford-upon-Avon]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Thompson|1999|p=142}}</ref> Their burgeoning reputation was apparent by the time of their next visit in May 1746, when a surviving letter from a local schoolmaster described them as "a Company of Strolling-Players ... much ye best Set I have seen out of London, & in which opinion I am far from being singular".<ref>{{Harvnb|McManaway|1949|p=299}}</ref> The company returned to Stratford again later that year, when their performance of ''[[Othello]]'' on 9 September – raising money to restore the memorial bust of [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] in [[Church of the Holy Trinity, Stratford-upon-Avon|Holy Trinity Church]] – was the earliest recorded performance of a play by Shakespeare in the playwright's home town.<ref>{{Harvnb|Highfill|Burnim|Langhans||1993|p=260}}</ref>

Over the following decades the company toured widely, performing in town halls, barns, schoolhouses and guildhalls throughout the [[English Midlands]] and [[Wales]].<ref name="Thompson 1999 143">{{Harvnb|Thompson|1999|p=143}}</ref> Their reputation was such that they were able to play long seasons at each venue – 23 weeks at [[Ludlow]] in 1758 and seventeen weeks at [[Brecon]] in 1764<ref name="Thompson 1999 143"/> – and their repertoire was wide: as well as [[William Shakespeare|Shakespeare]] it included works by [[William Congreve|Congreve]], [[John Dryden|Dryden]], [[Nicholas Rowe (writer)|Rowe]], [[Nathaniel Lee|Lee]], [[Richard Steele|Steele]] and [[John Vanbrugh|Vanbrugh]], and extended to [[pantomime]], [[music]] and [[dance]].<ref name="McManaway 1949 307">{{Harvnb|McManaway|1949|p=307}}</ref> Their performances also had a keen sense of spectacle: in [[Hereford]] in 1753 they presented ''[[Romeo and Juliet]]'' with the "Grand Funeral Procession and Solemn Dirge set to Music by Signor Pasqualli",<ref name="McManaway 1949 307"/> and at [[Gloucester]] in 1747 they performed ''[[Henry VIII (play)|Henry VIII]]'' "with the whole ceremony of the coronation of Queen Anne Bullen and the military ceremony of the Champion (on horse-back) in Westminster Hall. The Robes, Armour, Canopy and Bishops' and Judges' dresses and all the decorations of the play entirely new".<ref name="Highfill 1993 261">{{Harvnb|Highfill|Burnim|Langhans||1993|p=261}}</ref>

===Kemble===
[[File:Harlow The Court for the Trial of Queen Katharine.jpg|thumb|right|Members of the [[Kemble family]], including [[Sarah Siddons]] and [[John Philip Kemble]], performing at the [[Royal Opera House|Theatre Royal, Covent Garden]] in 1806]]The major turning point in the company's existence took place in 1751 when [[Richard Yates (actor)|Richard Yates]]' company from London's [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane]] opened the purpose-built [[King Street Theatre]] in Birmingham to compete with the smaller venue in Moor Street.<ref>{{Citation|last=Price|first=Victor J.|year=1988|title=Birmingham theatres: concert and music halls, 1740-1988|publication-place=Studley|publisher=Brewin Books|page=1|isbn=0-947731-35-0}}</ref> Ward's reaction to this invasion of his long-held territory was ill-tempered – the contemporary actor [[Charles Lee Lewes]] records him describing the newcomers as "drawling, face-making puppies" and promising to "work the dogs a penn'orth for daring to cross my circuit"<ref>{{Citation|last1=Lewes|first1=Charles Lee|year=1805|title=Memoirs of Charles Lee Lewes: containing anecdotes, historical and biographical, of the English and Scottish stages, during a period of forty years|volume=1|publication-place=London|publisher=Richard Phillips|page=89|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gM5MAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA89|accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref> – and Ward responded by advertising in the London newspapers for "capital performers" to join him in Birmingham.<ref name="Thompson 1999 143"/> This was pivotal moment in theatrical history, as it was this advertisement that brought [[Roger Kemble]] to Birmingham to join the company, and the following June in [[Cirencester]] Kemble married the Wards' daughter Sarah.<ref>{{Harvnb|McManaway|1949|pp=306}}</ref> Of the couple's twelve children each that survived into adulthood went onto the stage, all except one married performers, and all were to start their careers performing with the Warwickshire Company of Comedians: this marked the origin of the [[Kemble family]], who were to dominate the English stage over the following decades.<ref>{{Harvnb|Highfill|Burnim|Langhans||1982|pp=390–391}}</ref>

Several sources relate the Wards' anger at their daughter Sarah's elopement: she was not yet 16 and although a "main prop" of her father's in the "comic province", they felt that "an actor's existence was the last into which they wished her to drift".<ref>{{Harvnb|McManaway|1949|pp=305–306}}</ref> The Kembles were readmitted into the company, however, with Ward justifying his "sullen forgiveness" in the light of his low opinion of his new son-in-law's talents, telling his daughter "I forbade you to marry an actor. You have not disobeyed me since the man you have married neither is nor ever can be an actor".<ref>{{Harvnb|McManaway|1949|p=306}}</ref> Although the Kembles left the company and toured independently between 1761 and 1763, the Wards retired to [[Leominster]] in 1766 and Roger Kemble took over its management on 24 May of that year.<ref>{{Harvnb|Highfill|Burnim|Langhans||1982|p=389}}</ref> By the time the company appeared at [[Worcester]] in 1767 they were described as "Mr Kemble's Company of Comedians", with the cast featuring the Kembles' 14-year-old daughter Sarah – the future [[Sarah Siddons]] – and their 12-year-old son [[John Philip Kemble]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Price|1948|p=42}}; {{Harvnb|Highfill|Burnim|Langhans||1982|p=391}}</ref>

Kemble retired in 1781 and the company's stock and goodwill was split between two of the company's members: [[John Boles Watson]], who formed the "Cheltenham Company of Comedians" and established it as the resident company at his newly built [[Theatre Royal, Cheltenham|Cheltenham Playhouse]], and [[Henry Masterman]].<ref>{{Citation|last1=Denning|first1=Anthony|last2=Ranger|first2=Paul|year=1993|title=Theatre in the Cotswolds|publication-place=London|publisher=Society for Theatre Research|pages=1–2|isbn=0-85430-054-6}}; {{Harvnb|Price|1948|p=44}}</ref>

==Reputation and legacy==
The growth of the reputation of the Warwickshire Company of Comedians marked the birth of Birmingham's theatrical tradition, which was well established by 1750,<ref name="Money" /> and further extended this influence to the surrounding counties – they "made the temporary theatre in barn, hall or inn the centre of polite provincial life and brought London tastes and diversions to the country towns".<ref name="Highfill 1993 261"/> 

Under Ward the company's performances were of a much higher standard than that typical of [[strolling players]], being more comparable to those of the major [[London]] companies, with whom Ward and several of his company had considerable experience and with whose development they maintained a lively interest.<ref>{{Harvnb|Price|1948|pp=39–41, 42}}; {{Harvnb|McManaway|1949|pp=299, 304}}; {{Harvnb|Highfill|Burnim|Langhans||1993|p=261}}</ref> The high regard in which the company was held was recorded by the contemporary actor [[Charles Lee Lewes]], whose memoirs describe the "Great Ward" and his "very great company at Birmingham: many of them are no less than Londoners".<ref>{{Citation|last1=Lewes|first1=Charles Lee|year=1805|title=Memoirs of Charles Lee Lewes: containing anecdotes, historical and biographical, of the English and Scottish stages, during a period of forty years|volume=2|publication-place=London|publisher=Richard Phillips|page=130|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=glAOAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA130|accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref> [[Thomas Holcroft]], who acted with the company in the 1770s, recalled that in Kemble's time too it was "more respectable than many other companies of strolling players".<ref>{{Citation|last1=Holcroft|first1=Thomas|publication-date=1856|year=1810|title=Memoirs of the late Thomas Holcroft: written by himself; and continued to the time of his death|volume=17|series=The Traveller's Library|publication-place=London|publisher=Longman, Brown, Green and Longmans|page=81|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ksXVAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA81|accessdate=2011-05-23}}</ref> 

The principle importance of the company, however, lies in its role in the genesis of the [[Kemble family]], who were generally thought to have received their beauty and talent from the Wards and whose emergence saw actors with provincial origins for the first time leading rather than following the London stage.<ref>{{Harvnb|Highfill|Burnim|Langhans||1993|p=261}}; {{Harvnb|McManaway|1949|p=309}}; {{Harvnb|Thomson|2004}}</ref> Annotations from Ward's surviving [[prompt book]]s show that he was familiar with [[early texts of Shakespeare's works]] and was restoring Shakespeare's original text at an earlier date and more comprehensively even than [[David Garrick]],<ref>{{Harvnb|McManaway|1949|pp=313–314}}</ref> and also suggest that changes to the staging of ''[[Hamlet]]'' introduced to London as innovations by John Phillip Kemble had been practiced by Ward's company as early as 1740.<ref>{{Harvnb|Thompson|1999|p=139}}</ref> While tradition has it that Sarah Siddons "learnt her trade" between her initial unsuccessful appearance at [[Theatre Royal, Drury Lane|Drury Lane]] in 1775 and her triumphant return in 1782, it is equally possible that it was popular taste in London that had caught up in the meantime with her style, which was more suited to the emerging [[romanticism]] than the existing fashionable [[neoclassicism]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Trussler|first=Simon|publication-date=2000|year=1994|title=The Cambridge illustrated history of British theatre|publication-place=Cambridge|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=206|isbn=0-521-41913-1}}</ref>

